	The Neuroscience of Aging and Cognition 
International Encyclopedia of Education 
Close 
You are not entitled to access the full text of this document   The Neuroscience of Aging and Cognition 
International Encyclopedia of Education , 2010 , Pages 340-344 
W.J. Hoyer, B. Bessette-Symons 
 
Abstract 
Throughout the life span, environmental factors, genetic factors, the individual's actions and experiences, and inevitable changes in the functioning of neurobiological mechanisms interact to produce a range of effects on the cognitive abilities of individuals as they grow older. Some individuals show only minor deficits in particular forms of cognition as they grow older, while other individuals show substantial declines in various aspects of memory and learning. Healthy older adults usually show deficits in particular situations such as those that require the management and coordination of multiple tasks or that involve detailed recollection of events or experiences. Age-related deficits are most prominent in cognitive tasks that are particularly dependent on hippocampal and prefrontal brain circuitry. This article discusses normal age-related changes in learning and memory from a cognitive neuroscience perspective. 
 
