	Evolutionary and Developmental Issues in Cognitive Neur... 
Encyclopedia of Behavioral Neuroscience 
Close 
You are not entitled to access the full text of this document   Evolutionary and Developmental Issues in Cognitive Neuroscience 
Encyclopedia of Behavioral Neuroscience , 2010 , Pages 512-516 
S.A. Bunge, T.M. Preuss 
 
Abstract 
Most cognitive neuroscience research to date has focused on brain mechanisms. We can gain additional insights into the neural basis of cognition and action by considering how this finely tuned organ came to be, both from an evolutionary and a developmental perspective. This article focuses primarily on developmental and evolutionary changes in higher cognitive functions, in particular the ability to reason about the world and about others’ mental states. These functions are supported by neural circuits involving prefrontal cortex, a part of the brain that has expanded over evolution and that develops slowly over childhood and adolescence in humans. 
 
PDF (76 K) 
	Neuropsychology of Primate Reward Processes 
Encyclopedia of Neuroscience 
Close 
You are not entitled to access the full text of this document   Neuropsychology of Primate Reward Processes 
Encyclopedia of Neuroscience , 2009 , Pages 993-999 
E.A. Murray 
 
Abstract 
All animals attach positive value to stimuli associated with rewards and reproduce actions that lead to positive outcomes. The unique features of reward processes in primates involve the contributions of the granular prefrontal cortex. These areas, the most prominent parts of the prefrontal cortex in primates, lack homologs in other mammals. Together with other cortical areas, the granular prefrontal cortex produces a uniquely primate way of processing rewards, and it does so in large part through its interactions with the amygdala and basal ganglia. 
 
PDF (360 K) 
	Emotion-Cognition Interactions 
Encyclopedia of Behavioral Neuroscience 
Close 
You are not entitled to access the full text of this document   Emotion–Cognition Interactions 
Encyclopedia of Behavioral Neuroscience , 2010 , Pages 469-476 
K.S. LaBar 
 
Abstract 
Limbic forebrain regions are anatomically positioned to integrate cortical and subcortical processing streams that mediate cognitive and emotional functions. Feedback projections to sensory cortices bias perceptual systems to process stimuli of high significance. The amygdala is critical for learning contingencies in the environment that predict emotional outcomes and for modulating explicit memory processes in the hippocampus. The anterior cingulate gyrus and ventromedial and orbital prefrontal cortices serve as interfaces that link emotional information processing and attentional control systems to guide goal-directed behavior. Dysregulation of the balance between affective and cognitive systems is a hallmark of anxiety and mood disorders. 
 
